\begin_layout Problem
Return to the rubber band problem from the mid-semester assessment.
 We arrived at
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dG=-SdT+Vdp+fdL.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that we can write the force as the sum of an enthalpic term and an
 entropic term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}-T\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the Maxwell relation derived previously, along with the data in the
 graph, estimate (numerically) the fraction of the elasticity of the rubber
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

) that comes from the entropic term.
 Because you’re working with ratios, the distinction between force and modulus
 doesn’t matter ─ the geometrical factors that connect them cancel out.
 Which term (enthalpic or entropic) dominates?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From your result, does the rubber band get warmer or colder when you stretch
 it? When it retracts to its original length? If you have a rubber band
 handy, test your conclusion empirically and report the results.
 (Lips are sensitive differential thermometers.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Let's start by writing the expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dG=-SdT+Vdp+fdL.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
From that expression we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\left(\frac{\partial G}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p},
\]

\end_inset

and on the other hand, the definition of Gibbs free energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=H-TS,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the enthalpy, and from this definition, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial G}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}-\left(\frac{\partial\left(TS\right)}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p},
\]

\end_inset

but because we're keeping the temperature constant we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial G}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}-T\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we can obtain the following expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}-T\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we can see that the force can be written in terms of an enthalpic
 term and an entropic term.
 And even more, the previous equation has the following functional form
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=mT+b,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=-\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}\hspace{1em}\&\hspace{1em}b=\left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p},
\]

\end_inset

but from the figure we can see that the slope is positive, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $m>0$
\end_inset

, and this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}<0,
\]

\end_inset

which means that stretching brings makes the system more ordered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, we are going to calculate the contribution of the entropic term, this
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\partial S}{\partial L}\right)_{T,p}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta T}\approx\frac{0.22-0.17}{200-140},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies m\approx\frac{0.05}{60}\approx0.00083,
\]

\end_inset

thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\approx0.00083\frac{N}{mm^{2}K},
\]

\end_inset

and even more, from the figure we can see that the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, this is, the term associated to the enthalpy is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-2}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, for the the entropic term we have: fixing the temperature
 at around 200, we have the product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
mT & \approx0.00083\times200,\\
 & \approx0.17,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

but from the figure we can see that, 
\begin_inset Formula $b<0.17$
\end_inset

, and this is if we assume that the behavior is linear for all temperatures,
 something that sounds weird, but at first approximation sees reasonable.
 And with this analysis we can see that 
\series bold
the entropic term dominates
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, if we stretch the rubber that means we're in some sense in high
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and this implies that the temperature should be higher, something that
 agrees with our everyday experience when we stretch a rubber band.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
