\begin_layout Problem
In this problem you will calculate analytically the vibrational contribution
 to the energy of a diatomic molecule as a function of temperature, and,
 by making suitable approximations, consider the behavior in the low- and
 high-temperature limits.
 Model the molecule quantum mechanically as a particle in a three-dimensional
 infinite square (i.e.
 cubical) well of side length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that is also able to vibrate internally at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Represent the vibrational as a quantum harmonic oscillator.
 The center-of-mass and vibrational degrees of freedom are independent.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What are the quantum numbers that define a microstate of the molecule? What
 is the energy of the microstate in terms of those quantum numbers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 You can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is very large, so that the spacing between center-of-mass states is much
 smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, but do not assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

 is small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle U\right\rangle =k_{B}T^{2}\frac{\partial\ln Z}{\partial T}
\]

\end_inset

find the average energy of the molecule at low temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\ll\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Compare your result to what is expected from classical equipartition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find the average energy of the molecule at high temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\gg\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Compare your result to what is expected from classical equipartition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How does this calculation relate to the analysis we did in HW 1, Prob 5.?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Sol.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Formally, we have to solve the Schrödinger equation, and in this case we
 have two contributions to the energy, one is given by the particle in a
 box, and the other is given by the vibration modes.
 In the case of a particle in a box, which is the contribution for the translati
onal degrees of freedom, we have a contribution in the energy as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{i}^{\left(fp\right)}=\frac{\hbar^{2}n_{i}^{2}}{2m},\hspace{1em}i\in\left\{ x,y,z\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

and the contribution for the vibrational degrees of freedom is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{j}^{\left(sho\right)}=\left(n_{j}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\hbar\omega,\hspace{1em}j\in\{1,2\},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, the energy total energy is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{ij}=E_{i}^{\left(fp\right)}+E_{j}^{\left(sho\right)},
\]

\end_inset

and there's a reason for the notation, which will be clear in a moment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Once we have the energies, we can write the partition function, but there's
 a nice result which I want to exploit: if the total energy of s system
 can be decomposed in a sum of various independent contributions, them then
 the total partition function is the product of several partition functions,
 this is, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{ij}=E_{i}^{\left(a\right)}+E_{j}^{\left(b\right)},
\]

\end_inset

then, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z & =\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\exp\left[-\beta\left(E_{i}^{\left(a\right)}+E_{j}^{\left(b\right)}\right)\right],\\
 & =\sum_{i}\exp\left[-\beta E_{i}^{\left(a\right)}\right]\sum_{j}\exp\left[-\beta+E_{j}^{\left(b\right)}\right],\\
 & =Z_{a}Z_{b},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and with this result at hand, we know that we usually deal with 
\begin_inset Formula $ln\left(Z\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 itself, and in this case we have exactly that, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ln Z & =\ln\left(Z_{a}Z_{b}\right),\\
 & =\ln Z_{a}+\ln Z_{b},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

therefore the energy will be given as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle U\right\rangle =k_{B}T^{2}\frac{\partial\ln Z_{a}Z_{b}}{\partial T},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left\langle U\right\rangle =k_{B}T^{2}\left(\frac{\partial\ln Z_{a}}{\partial T}+\frac{\partial\ln Z_{b}}{\partial T}\right),
\]

\end_inset

Now, with this in mind, we have, our particular problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\exp\left[-\beta\left(E_{i}^{\left(fp\right)}+E_{j}^{\left(sho\right)}\right)\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies Z=\sum_{i}\exp\left[-\beta E_{i}^{\left(fp\right)}\right]\sum_{j}\exp\left[-\beta E_{j}^{\left(sho\right)}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have to calculate the contribution for each one this is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{fp}\hspace{1em}\&\hspace{1em}Z_{sho},
\]

\end_inset

but using the same idea we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{fp}=Z_{1},\hspace{1em}\&\hspace{1em}Z_{sho}=Z_{2}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the partition functions of the particle in a box, and the simple harmonic
 oscillator, but in 1D, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{trans}=Vn_{Q},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{Q}$
\end_inset

 is the quantum concentration, which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{Q}=\frac{1}{\hbar^{3}}\left(\frac{mk_{B}T}{2\pi}\right)^{3/2},
\]

\end_inset

but let's rewrite it in a more convenient way, this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z_{trans} & =\frac{V}{\hbar^{3}}\left(\frac{m}{2\pi}\right)^{3/2}\left(k_{B}T\right)^{3/2},\\
Z_{trans} & =\alpha\beta^{-3/2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=\frac{V}{\hbar^{3}}\left(\frac{m}{2\pi}\right)^{3/2},\hspace{1em}\beta=\frac{1}{k_{B}T}
\]

\end_inset

and for the simple harmonic oscillator we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{vib}=\frac{\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\beta\hbar\omega\right)}{1-\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On the other hand, for this kind of calculations it's easier to take derivatives
 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, or at least for the energy it's quite convenient, this using the chain
 rule we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=k_{B}T^{2}\frac{\partial\ln Z}{\partial T}=-\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln Z,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies U=-\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln Z,
\]

\end_inset

but as stated before the partition function is the product of two independent
 contributions, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U & =U_{trans}+U_{vib},\\
 & =-\left[\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln Z_{trans}+-\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln Z_{vib}\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{trans}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{trans} & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln Z_{trans}\\
 & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\left[\ln\left(\alpha\beta^{-3/2}\right)\right],\\
 & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\left[\ln\alpha-\frac{3}{2}\ln\beta\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{trans}=\frac{3}{2}\frac{d}{d\beta}\ln\beta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies U_{trans}=\frac{3}{2}\frac{1}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{trans}=\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{vib}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{vib} & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\left[\ln\left(\frac{\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\beta\hbar\omega\right)}{1-\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)}\right)\right],\\
 & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\left[\ln\left(\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\beta\hbar\omega\right)\right)-\ln\left(1-\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)\right)\right],\\
 & =-\frac{d}{d\beta}\left[-\frac{1}{2}\beta\hbar\omega-\ln\left(1-\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)\right)\right],\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega+\frac{\hbar\omega\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)}{1-\exp\left(-\beta\hbar\omega\right)},\\
 & =\hbar\omega\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\exp\left(\beta\hbar\omega\right)-1}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{vib}=\hbar\omega\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\exp\left(\beta\hbar\omega\right)-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and the total contribution is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T+\hbar\omega\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\exp\left(\beta\hbar\omega\right)-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now, in the limit given 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{B}T\ll\hbar\omega\implies1\ll\beta\hbar\omega,
\]

\end_inset

the term with the exponential goes to infinity and the denominator goes
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, and the other factor is just a constant, thus we and up with the result
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\approx\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T,
\]

\end_inset

which matches with the classical result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, in the case of high temperature, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T\gg\hbar\omega$
\end_inset

, and this implies that we can Taylor expand the term with the exponential
 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\exp\left(\beta\hbar\omega\right)-1}\approx\frac{1}{\beta\hbar\omega},
\]

\end_inset

thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U & \approx\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T+\hbar\omega\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta\hbar\omega}\right),\\
 & \approx\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T+\frac{\hbar\omega}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from this we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\approx\frac{3}{2}k_{B}T+k_{B}T,
\]

\end_inset

this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\approx\frac{5}{2}k_{B}T,
\]

\end_inset

which again, matches with the equipartition theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This result is in agreement with the analysis presented in the HW 1, in
 which we found the following: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the spacings between vibrational levels and between rotational levels about
 the molecular axis are much larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, which implies that classical thermodynamics, including the equipartition
 theorem, do not apply
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 And even more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

..for rotations about the two axes perpendicular to the molecular axis, however,
 the spacings between energy levels are much smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, so equipartition does apply.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
