\begin_layout Problem
The molar concentration of carbon dioxide in the Earth’s atmosphere is currently
 about 420 ppm (
\begin_inset Formula $0.042%\%
$
\end_inset

), and rising.
 Even if we were to stop adding 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 , it will take hundreds of years for what is already there to be removed
 by natural processes.
 It has therefore been proposed that we actively remove 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 from the atmosphere, liquify it, and inject it deep underground or deep
 into the ocean, where the pressure is sufficient to keep it liquid and,
 hopefully, in place for geological times.
 In this problem, you will examine the minimum energy cost of such an approach
 set by fundamental principles of thermodynamics.
 (Practical technologies will probably require at least twice that much
 energy.)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let’s suppose we want to isolate and liquify 1 kg of 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 What is the volume of air that contains that much 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

? How many moles of 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 does it contain? How many moles of air?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Separating the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 means going from a state of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 containing the mixed gas, to a state in which there is a volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{CO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 that contains just 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 , and a volume (
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}–V_{CO_{2}}$
\end_inset

) that contains just air.
 Assume that the temperature and pressure remain constant.
 What is the change in entropy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 in this process? What is the change in entropy of the air?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the minimum energy input required to effect this separation? Give
 an answer in J/kg
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
At room temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 liquifies at a pressure of about 56 
\begin_inset Formula $atm$
\end_inset

.
 How much work is required to compress the separated 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 isothermally to that pressure? Give an answer in J/kg
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To put these numbers in some perspective, compare the energy required to
 separate and liquify the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 released annually in the US to the country’s annual electricity consumption.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Let's start with the solution:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The ppm of CO2 in the atmosphere is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $421$
\end_inset

, which is around 
\begin_inset Formula $0.04\%$
\end_inset

 of the gases in the atmosphere, therefore if we assume that we can model
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 as an ideal gas, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pV=nRT,
\]

\end_inset

thus using the fact that the molar mass of the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 is also given by 
\begin_inset Formula $44.01$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=n\frac{RT}{p}.
\]

\end_inset

But we need to convert the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 mass to moles, and for that we are going to use using its molar mass as
 follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{moles of }CO_{2}=\frac{\text{mass of }CO_{2}}{\text{molar mass of }CO_{2}\times\text{moles of }CO_{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{moles of }CO_{2}=0.0226\text{ mol},
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand the molar mass of air, on average is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $28.97g/mol$
\end_inset

, and after plug those quantities in the ideal gas equation we have that
 the volume occupied by 1 kg of 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by approximately 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=86296.17\text{ L}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the change in entropy let's model this as an isobaric compression, and
 for this we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ΔS=nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{f}}{V_{i}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

thus, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $CO_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{CO_{2}}=nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{CO_{2}}}{V_{0}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and in the same way, for the air, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta S_{air}=nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{0}-V_{CO_{2}}}{V_{0}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

