\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For this process we're going to model it as an isothermal compression, thus
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=
\]

\end_inset

To calculate the work required to compress the separated CO2 isothermally
 to a pressure of 56 atm, we can use the formula for the work done during
 an isothermal compression of a gas:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=-\int_{V_{i}}^{V_{f}}P\,dV,
\]

\end_inset

but because the compression is isothermal, the pressure and temperature
 remain constant, thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=-P\int_{V_{i}}^{V_{f}}dV,
\]

\end_inset

but again, the compression is isothermal, we can use the ideal gas law to
 relate the initial and final volumes as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i}V_{i}=p_{f}V_{f}=\text{constant},
\]

\end_inset

and if assume that the initial pressure is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 atm, and the final is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f}=56$
\end_inset

 atm, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{i}=56V_{f},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=-P\int_{V_{i}}^{V_{f}}dV,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=55pV_{f},
\]

\end_inset

now using the fact that the work done per unit mass is equal to W divided
 by the mass of CO2, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\frac{55pV}{m_{CO_{2}}},
\]

\end_inset

and now, in order to find 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{f}$
\end_inset

 we can use the fact that at room temperature, the volume occupied by 1
 kg of liquid CO2 at 56 atm pressure would be the reciprocal of its density
 at that pressure.
 The density of liquid CO2 at 56 atm is approximately 0.881 kg/L, thus if
 we put the numbers, this will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\approx3469.38\left[\frac{J}{kg}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
