\begin_layout Problem
In this problem you will apply the idea of chemical potential to two very
 different real-world contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Centrifugal isotope separation.
 Gas centrifuges are used to separate isotopes of uranium to produce fuel
 that is sufficiently enriched for fission applications.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider a cylinder of gas, of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, rotating at angular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 In order to move a particle inward by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $–dr$
\end_inset

, one must exert an inward force equal to the centripetal force at that
 radius, doing work on the particle.
 Use this fact to write an expression for the total chemical potential as
 a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use your result in (1a) to determine the ratio of the gas density at radius
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to the density at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In uranium enrichment, the goal is to increase the concentration of the
 fissile isotope 
\begin_inset Formula $^{235}U$
\end_inset

, which is naturally only 0.7%, with the remainder being almost entirely
 non-fissile 
\begin_inset Formula $^{238}U$
\end_inset

.
 Because uranium is not normally a gas, it is first reacted with fluorine
 to make 
\begin_inset Formula $UF_{6}$
\end_inset

 .
 A typical enrichment centrifuge may have a radius of 0.2 m and rotate at
 a speed of 1500 revolutions per second.
 At the perimeter of the centrifuge, will the concentration of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{235}U$
\end_inset

 be enhanced or reduced? What will be the new concentration at that point?
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Sap in trees.
 Giant sequoias are among the tallest trees in the world, reaching heights
 of 100 m.
 This raises an interesting question: how does sap get to the top of the
 tree? Atmospheric pressure cannot support a column of water higher than
 about 10 m.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider a very simplified model of sap in the tree as represented by a
 thin vertical tube filled with liquid water.
 The bottom is immersed in a pool of water, and the density of water vapor
 in the air just above the water is 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The top is at height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, where the relative humidity is 
\begin_inset Formula $r=n(h)/n_{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 Assume that the water in the tube is in diffusive equilibrium with the
 water vapor in the air at both the top and bottom of the tube.
 If that is the case, what is the difference in internal chemical potential
 
\begin_inset Formula $Δ\mu_{int}$
\end_inset

 between the top and the bottom?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In addition, there is an external chemical potential difference due to the
 change in gravitational potential energy.
 Taking this into account, what is the total chemical potential difference
 (internal + external) between the top and the bottom?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $μ_{tot}(h)<μ_{tot}(0)$
\end_inset

, then water will flow upwards in the tube, feeding the top of the tree.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $μ_{tot}(h)≥μ_{tot}(0)$
\end_inset

, upward flow will stop.
 Using this principle, find the maximum height 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{max}$
\end_inset

 to which the tree can move sap, as a function of the relative humidity
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Find the numerical value for r = 90%.
 Is your answer consistent with the existence of giant sequoias?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Before doing any calculation I would like to write some definitions that
 are useful for the following discussion: let's suppose we have two systems
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, each one with it's own thermodynamical parameters, if we put the system
 in thermal contact and let them exchange particles, after some time, we
 will reach equilibrium, assuming the connected system are closed.
 Thus the condition for diffusive equilibrium can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{1}=\mu_{2}=\mu_{0},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

 represents the chemical potential of the system at some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point of reference
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Having said that, we know that particles flow from high chemical potential
 to lower chemical potential, in the same way as we observe heat flow, thus
 a difference in chemical potential acts in some sense as a driving force
 for the transfer or particles.
 And even more, we know that only differences in chemical potential have
 physical meaning, and we're also free to choose our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 potential reference.
 Now, with this in mind, we know that when a potential is present, we can
 express the total chemical potential as the sum of the internal chemical
 potential and a the external chemical potential, and the former is defined
 as the potential energy per particle in the external potential, this is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mu_{tot}=\Delta\mu_{int}+\Delta\mu_{ext}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, in the following two problems I'm going to model the system as an ideal
 gas, I know this is not very accurate, in particular for the tree problem,
 but still, it'll give us a good feeling of the system, and for this reason
 I think it's important to write the chemical potential for an ideal gas,
 this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=k_{B}T\ln\left(n\lambda_{th}^{3}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{Q}^{-1/3}=\lambda_{th},
\]

\end_inset

thus, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n}{n_{Q}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Centrifugal Isotope Separation: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In this case the external potential is given by the centripetal force, which
 is given by the following expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{c}=ma_{c},
\]

\end_inset

where we know 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{c}=\omega^{2}r$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the angular velocity.
 Thus from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{c}=m\omega^{2}r,
\]

\end_inset

but as stated in the problem, in order to move a particle inward by an amount
 
\begin_inset Formula $–dr$
\end_inset

, one must exert an inward force equal to the centripetal force at that
 radius, doing work on the particle, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-m\omega^{2}rdr,
\]

\end_inset

but, on the other hand, by definition we know that the chemical potential
 is the amount of energy we need in order to add one particle to the system,
 thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=-m\omega^{2}\int rdr,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\mu=-\frac{m}{2}\omega^{2}r^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, with this we have that the total chemical potential is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{tot}=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n\left(r\right)}{n_{Q}}\right)-\frac{m}{2}\omega^{2}r^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, if we imposing the condition of diffusive equilibrium, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{tot}=\mu_{0},
\]

\end_inset

and even more assuming an ideal gas, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{tot}=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n\left(r\right)}{n_{Q}}\right)-\frac{m}{2}\omega^{2}r^{2}=\mu_{0},
\]

\end_inset

and in this case we choose our reference potential such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{0}=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n_{Q}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}=n\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n\left(r\right)}{n_{Q}}\right)-\frac{m}{2}\omega^{2}r^{2}=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n_{Q}}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\ln\left(\frac{n\left(r\right)}{n_{Q}}\frac{n_{Q}}{n_{0}}\right)=\frac{m}{2k_{B}T}\omega^{2}r^{2},
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\left(r\right)=n_{0}\exp\left(\frac{m\omega^{2}r^{2}}{2k_{B}T}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Tree:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
As above, if we assume that the system is in diffusive equilibrium, and
 there are no external fields in the system, and even more, approximating
 the problem as an ideal gas, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mu_{int}=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n}{n_{Q}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{0}r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, with the previous result and assuming an external potential due to
 the gravitational field we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\mu_{ext}=mgh,
\]

\end_inset

and even more, assuming again, diffusive equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{tot}=\mu_{0},
\]

\end_inset

such that our reference point is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n_{Q}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n}{n_{Q}}\right)+mgh=k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n_{Q}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
mgh=-k_{B}T\ln\left(\frac{n}{n_{Q}}\frac{n_{Q}}{n_{0}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and from this we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=\frac{k_{B}T}{mg}\ln\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{n}{n_{0}}=r,
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=\frac{k_{B}T}{mg}\ln\left(\frac{1}{r}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, if we consider the humidity as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(r\right)/n_{0}=0.9$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=300$
\end_inset

 K, and the mass of water as 
\begin_inset Formula $m=18$
\end_inset

 g, then, then numerical value, after the corresponding conversions will
 be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h=1490.04\text{ m,}
\]

\end_inset

which is a really high number, consistent in some sense with the giant sequoias,
 but I not expect to have a good map with a real tree, because I'm not sure
 if the sap of a tree can be well modeled by an ideal, gas, I suspect that
 this is not the case, however, this give us some insight into the physical
 mechanism.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
